Â The minimally collectable second gun is NOT available separately at this time.  Lots of these guns have been repainted. The original paint was not the best quality, so the repainted ones generally look better than the originals and is the first indication of repainting. On WOLVERINE-marked guns, that name should be in white-ish paint (it is not true white) overlay on black. Otherwise, most likely it is a repainted gun. To a typical collector, these repainted guns areÂ not a valuable collector's item any longer, but become "shooters".  More images on request.Â   It's been difficult to establish a fair price for this gun, as so very few have been sold in the last 10 years that are marked WOLVERINE. To a "traditional" collector, those are the only true Whitney Wolverines, and all else is not quite a true Wolverine. There is no difference, of course, in the guns and their function.Â   Also, perhaps best to explain "rare". To a collector, that can mean one of a kind or not more than 5 in existence. Among guns, a total quantity in existence of perhaps 200 qualifies, for some guns. For example, only about 30 SAKO TriAce were imported into the USA, so the gun is rare IN THE USA, but not world-wide. About 150 of their Finnmaster were made in two versions, so each version worldwide could be considered rare for a gun, but not quite there if the 5 or fewer criterion is used.  This gun is not that rare. But it is very very uncommon, with the WOLVERINE marking, so compared to other mass produced guns, at least it's borderline rare.  A few comments about this gun. It is a "backwards" design for any handgun, with the only true lockup being at the muzzle. The end result is a tolerable gun that is difficult to reassembly correctly (the reason so many are chipped at the hammer area), with moderate accuracy. It is not as accurate as the Hi Standard Victor, and far inferior to the Hammerli 208 or Walther GSP. Also unlike those guns, trigger pull and position are not adjustable. These are NOT target guns by ANY standard, and due to the basic design, can NOT be converted into one of that accuracy or quality.  The collector world for these guns is "strange" despite a very concise book on their history, which interestingly, does not mention the unusual overall design, its potential values and failures as an accurate pistol. The early guns like this one were marked Wolverine as he mentions, and this was removed from the guns due to a trademark infringement suit against Whitney company. The resolution was to remove the marks from the gun, but leave the name on the boxes and inserts. A few of the guns are plated, most are not. A fair number of scrap parts were assembled into guns after the company failed. The box for this gun never had the yellow insert, probably because of the timing (suit filed, not settled, no decision on how to compromise). These guns are considered collector's items by some, or pastiches by others of scrap value only. Beauty is in the eye of the beholder, perhaps, as is value. For the optionalÂ more typical one, moderately heavy use, mechanically reconditioned for much less---- see third image. Â Available with purchase of this gun, in case a collector wants a "useable" gun of equal accuracy, as well so one can stay on the shelf, and the other be used. Price for both guns including 4 magazines, spare parts is $1650 plus shipping. Â  IL transfer on FOID after state police confirmation is possible, in the more forward-thinking areas that have not defined this gun as an assault weapon. NH transfer on any of the several appropriate NH IDs (with NH police dept confirmation) also is possible. FFL shipping and C&R FFL shipping can be provided as well, to licensee of your choice. However, be sure the gun can be delivered to you, due to local or state assault weapon bans.  Also available are : Hammerli 208 S and 215 S, Hammeril 215 (non-S) Walther GSP, Walther OSP (all versions, 10" barrel) Hi Standard Victors (Hamden, Â 5.5" bbl) Â steel and aluminum rib, Al ribbed oneÂ with full length barrel weight OEM. History of the Beretta 92FS
Designed in 1975 by Carlo Beretta, Giuseppe Mazzetti, and Vittorio Valle; the Beretta 92 (made in Italy) pistol is an evolution from the M1922 and M1951. Taking the open slide design from the M1922 and its alloy frame and locking barrel from the M1951. Along the way the Beretta 92 also adopted a direct feed and a "double-stacked" high capacity design to its magazine.

In order to meet the requirements of select law enforcement agencies, Beretta added a slide-mounted combined safety and docking lever. Thus the Beretta 92S was born and adopted by several Italian law enforcement and military units.

Eventually Beretta modified the 92SB (a special model with a firing pin block designed for the U.S. Air Force) with an enlarged hammer pin to stop the slide from flying off the frame in response to reports of defective slides during U.S. Military testing.

title: For Sale:  Uncommon Walther Model 9
postcontent:
I have for sale a rather uncommon Walther Model 9 vest pocket pistol. The pistol was initially released by Walther in 1921, and production of this then-popular weapon continued largely unchanged until 1945. It's chambered in 6.35mm (.25ACP) and has a 5-round single-stack magazine. The cartridge is discharged via a striker-fired mechanism, and as a result the pistol is able to be fully-functional in a significantly smaller package than would have been required if Walther had used a hammer-based design. The result of this design was the smallest-ever semi-automatic 6.35mm pistol, even to this day. The design was so popular that many other companies had to create similarly-sized (but larger) pistols in order to try to take business from Walther.

I purchased my Model 9 from a collector online who misstated the quality and condition of this particular example. I was made to believe that it has 97% finish or better, and that it was all-original. It is in just fine condition and functions well mechanically, but the finish is at maybe 90%, and I believe that the grips are too nice to be original. It's just a little too rough to keep in my Walther collection, so I'm hoping to find someone who will enjoy it for what it is: an honest, functional, little conversation piece with a fun history with which you don't have to worry about accidental fingerprint marks or letting people handle it.

I'm open to trades or partial trades for other Walther products, and would be happy to pitch in extra cash if you have something interesting. Please feel free to contact me with anything you'd be interested in trading.

Thanks,

Ian
